<br>
About the '/loc' hotkey kendrik suggested, I would advise adding a second line to it with '/doabilty n' where 'n' is the slot you put sense heading in (you DID put it into an ability slot, did you)? Keep mashing that key when in combat or running around, sooner or later (later as you start but it will become faster) your sense heading improves. Very useful for not getting lost and also, if like me, you do not like locs.<br>
<br>
About starting in Shar Val: Hail every NPC you see and talk to them. There are many tasks they give to you, several of those tasks they give you a free container for to fill. Also, for most things from the pit you do not get much money if you sell them to vendors. The reward is much better if you bring them to the NPC who is looking for them.<br>
<br>
Talk to Vah Shir from other houses, find out what they need to fulfill the tasks their Elders set them. Exchange things they need for things you need with them. That way, you will make friends as well as be able to leave the soon boring pit earlier.<br>
<br>
Talk to more experienced Vah Shir that seem to have time and ask them about the surroundings. My suggestion would be to go to the Thicket (south gate) as soon as you hunted all you need for the task from  your professional guild in the pit. As in the city, talk to every NPC. There are many quests for armor out there, know what you need for them (I suggest taking notes, as soon you will have too many tasks to remember). You often need four of a certain piece for the quests, as in the pit try making friends and fairly exchanging things so both of you get four of a thing you need as soon as possible.<br>
<br>
For Kati Sha, you will probably want to learn tailoring. Tailoring is a pain to learn. If you are not adverse to using the web, I would suggest looking up recepies at eqtraders.com. Me personally, I do not consider this cheating, as in a &quot;real&quot; world you could ask vendors and NPC tradespeople how things are made, in EQ they are very limited in their conversation. If you do not wish to use the web, ask more experienced PC Vah Shir about the recepies and what difficulty they are. Train as high as your Elder will train you, then make the easiest things first till you cannot learn from them anymore, then the next harder ones. Easiest after learning all you can are silk cords (3 threads) and tattered rockhopper armor (damaged hopper hide from the thicket and a pattern), which you can wear as well.<br>
<br>
Well, this is what I did and others may differ<br>
<br>
Shakatta - Vah Shir Kati Sha of the 13th rank, somewhat proficient at tailoring (Shadowed Hopperhide I cannot learn from anymore)<br>
